                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 815.77/84.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Tegucigalpa</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 7, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Minister for Foreign Affairs says that American forces were landed at Puerto
                    Cortés this morning; all were reembarked but one, who is stationed in the office
                    of the superintendent of the railroad. A communication was quoted from the
                    American Vice Consul at that port advising the Minister for Foreign Affairs that
                    the commander of the American war vessel had taken possession of the railroad
                    pending instructions. Firm but courteous protest was made by the Minister.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">White</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
